WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.920
Welcome to today's live demo.

00:00:01.920 --> 00:00:04.600
In Episode 5 of Posit Cloud Essentials,

00:00:04.600 --> 00:00:06.760
we're going to be diving deep into using the platform

00:00:06.760 --> 00:00:09.440
to teach data courses and workshops.

00:00:09.440 --> 00:00:11.040
If this is your first time watching,

00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:12.240
my name is Alex Chisholm,

00:00:12.240 --> 00:00:16.360
and I work on the Posit Cloud team here at Posit.

00:00:16.360 --> 00:00:19.200
I'm also really excited to have a co-speaker

00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:20.799
for the first time who knows a lot

00:00:20.799 --> 00:00:23.480
about the intersection of R and data science

00:00:23.480 --> 00:00:26.200
and education really as much as anyone.

00:00:26.200 --> 00:00:28.559
Mine, would you like to introduce yourself?

00:00:28.559 --> 00:00:30.680
Yeah, thanks for having me today.

00:00:30.680 --> 00:00:32.720
So my name is Nina Chetinkar-Arundel.

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:36.520
I'm a developer educator at Posit in the open source team,

00:00:36.520 --> 00:00:39.480
but I'm also a faculty member at Duke University.

00:00:39.480 --> 00:00:41.720
And I have been using Posit Cloud

00:00:41.720 --> 00:00:44.680
for quite a few years now at this point,

00:00:44.680 --> 00:00:48.439
at times as part of my on-campus teaching

00:00:48.439 --> 00:00:51.599
and at times for teaching workshops

00:00:51.599 --> 00:00:53.799
that are either short-term or long-term workshops

00:00:53.799 --> 00:00:54.639
outside of here.

00:00:54.639 --> 00:00:57.240
So I'm happy to share my experiences.

00:00:57.240 --> 00:00:58.080
Yeah, that's great.

00:00:58.480 --> 00:01:00.480
I'm very glad to have you here with us today.

00:01:00.480 --> 00:01:02.720
And before we get into the benefits

00:01:02.720 --> 00:01:04.760
of teaching with Posit Cloud,

00:01:04.760 --> 00:01:05.599
I just wanted to say,

00:01:05.599 --> 00:01:07.360
if you have any questions along the way,

00:01:07.360 --> 00:01:09.199
please drop them into the chat box.

00:01:09.199 --> 00:01:11.720
We will get to them in real time if we come across them,

00:01:11.720 --> 00:01:14.000
or we have time at the end to circle back

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:16.320
after the demo we're going to be running.

00:01:17.239 --> 00:01:18.680
So what I'd like to start with actually

00:01:18.680 --> 00:01:22.680
is before we as instructors were lucky enough

00:01:22.680 --> 00:01:26.239
to have cloud environments to teach,

00:01:26.239 --> 00:01:27.720
like what life was like,

00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:30.760
and I want to take you back to a troubling time in 2016,

00:01:30.760 --> 00:01:32.839
where I tried and failed for the first time

00:01:32.839 --> 00:01:35.639
to get students in like a data literacy type course

00:01:35.639 --> 00:01:37.480
up and running with coding.

00:01:37.480 --> 00:01:40.360
And everybody was really, really excited

00:01:40.360 --> 00:01:41.879
about the opportunity.

00:01:41.879 --> 00:01:43.440
So it was kind of disappointing the first time

00:01:43.440 --> 00:01:46.120
where we had everybody pull up their desktop IDEs

00:01:46.120 --> 00:01:47.839
and we spent the entire first class

00:01:47.839 --> 00:01:51.199
like troubleshooting individual pains

00:01:51.199 --> 00:01:52.360
that people were going through

00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:54.120
trying to get up and running, right?

00:01:54.120 --> 00:01:56.559
So like I couldn't get the right packages installed.

00:01:56.559 --> 00:01:58.360
I couldn't find the files

00:01:58.360 --> 00:02:00.440
that you're asking me to connect to.

00:02:00.440 --> 00:02:02.360
What even is a working directory?

00:02:02.360 --> 00:02:03.959
I'm on a different operating system.

00:02:03.959 --> 00:02:06.559
Like all of these questions would come up

00:02:06.559 --> 00:02:08.440
and it just, it became very difficult

00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:10.800
to have a starting point for all the students

00:02:10.800 --> 00:02:13.360
to start at the same place.

00:02:13.360 --> 00:02:14.960
I'm curious, Mina, from your perspective,

00:02:14.960 --> 00:02:17.479
I do have like one or multiple moments

00:02:17.479 --> 00:02:21.320
of painful teaching experiences from this type of pain.

00:02:22.320 --> 00:02:23.160
Yeah, I do.

00:02:23.160 --> 00:02:26.279
I, you know, I bet the pain is felt differently

00:02:26.279 --> 00:02:29.279
from the student side, but as an instructor,

00:02:29.279 --> 00:02:31.240
I can sort of pinpoint two things.

00:02:31.240 --> 00:02:36.240
One is when I would try to teach with IDEs

00:02:37.399 --> 00:02:41.479
sort of like on installed individually on student machines.

00:02:41.479 --> 00:02:45.119
One thing I realized is that I am not great

00:02:45.119 --> 00:02:47.720
at troubleshooting on an operating system

00:02:47.720 --> 00:02:48.759
different than my own.

00:02:49.440 --> 00:02:52.600
So I've been a Mac user for quite some time now

00:02:52.600 --> 00:02:56.679
as I've been learning to use R and RStudio.

00:02:56.679 --> 00:02:58.800
So I'm pretty familiar with when you install things

00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:01.039
where they go and how to troubleshoot them.

00:03:01.919 --> 00:03:05.119
And I have always felt awful

00:03:05.119 --> 00:03:08.240
when a student comes up to me with a Windows machine

00:03:08.240 --> 00:03:10.919
and what I tell them is, I don't know how to help you.

00:03:10.919 --> 00:03:12.600
Oh, but I can help your friend

00:03:12.600 --> 00:03:15.039
who has an operating system similar to mine.

00:03:15.039 --> 00:03:16.759
Or sometimes some students

00:03:16.759 --> 00:03:19.119
will have their operating systems

00:03:19.119 --> 00:03:20.559
in a different natural language

00:03:20.559 --> 00:03:22.440
than English or a language I speak.

00:03:22.440 --> 00:03:24.479
And that usually feels really bad too

00:03:24.479 --> 00:03:25.880
when I can't help them.

00:03:25.880 --> 00:03:28.720
Another thing though, is that for my classroom teaching,

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:32.520
I have been using some cloud version of RStudio,

00:03:32.520 --> 00:03:34.720
I wanna say forever.

00:03:34.720 --> 00:03:39.119
Back in the day, RStudio, the company would actually,

00:03:39.119 --> 00:03:41.080
you know, allow a few instructors

00:03:41.080 --> 00:03:43.960
to sort of run a hosted version

00:03:43.960 --> 00:03:48.960
of what was then RStudio server, I suppose.

00:03:50.119 --> 00:03:51.639
And I would use that.

00:03:51.639 --> 00:03:53.679
But something I had not realized

00:03:53.679 --> 00:03:58.119
is that when you distribute a data file to students

00:03:58.119 --> 00:03:59.960
and you're teaching in a computer lab,

00:03:59.960 --> 00:04:02.320
so the machines are not the students and not your own,

00:04:02.320 --> 00:04:03.919
but the universities,

00:04:03.919 --> 00:04:07.000
students might have no idea where the downloaded files go.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:08.880
So even if you, you know,

00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:11.559
think that you are 100% prepared to teach,

00:04:11.559 --> 00:04:14.240
you've even sort of set up your computing environment

00:04:14.240 --> 00:04:16.079
and you think things are ready to go,

00:04:16.079 --> 00:04:17.359
you go to the computer lab

00:04:17.359 --> 00:04:18.760
and the first thing you're faced with

00:04:18.760 --> 00:04:21.239
is where are the files are downloaded.

00:04:21.239 --> 00:04:23.279
And I remember spending about 20 minutes

00:04:23.279 --> 00:04:24.799
trying to get started with a class

00:04:24.799 --> 00:04:26.920
thinking this is not where I thought we would choke.

00:04:26.920 --> 00:04:29.040
So these things do happen.

00:04:29.040 --> 00:04:32.079
And it seems like it's very difficult to be prepared

00:04:32.079 --> 00:04:33.880
to teach in an environment different

00:04:33.880 --> 00:04:36.519
than one that you can access.

00:04:36.519 --> 00:04:39.440
Yeah, that's completely fair and accurate.

00:04:39.440 --> 00:04:40.600
I think that's where Pulsar Cloud

00:04:40.600 --> 00:04:43.839
has made teaching a lot easier for a lot of people.

00:04:43.839 --> 00:04:44.679
In my role here,

00:04:44.679 --> 00:04:47.040
I've worked with a lot of individual instructors

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:48.799
that are kind of running their own course

00:04:48.799 --> 00:04:50.160
within a university,

00:04:50.160 --> 00:04:52.480
also with entire departments

00:04:52.480 --> 00:04:54.519
that have multiple instructors that are coming on board

00:04:54.519 --> 00:04:57.079
and people that are just running workshops.

00:04:57.079 --> 00:05:00.399
But this ability to get students up and running

00:05:00.399 --> 00:05:01.839
with the same environment,

00:05:01.839 --> 00:05:04.079
the same files from the get-go,

00:05:04.079 --> 00:05:05.760
really it's just saved a lot of time

00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:07.880
on the instructor side.

00:05:07.880 --> 00:05:09.640
But as you mentioned from a student side as well,

00:05:09.640 --> 00:05:13.279
it doesn't lead to these burdens right away,

00:05:13.279 --> 00:05:15.519
which can be frustrating when you're just learning out,

00:05:15.519 --> 00:05:18.239
which takes away some of that excitement.

00:05:18.239 --> 00:05:23.239
So we feel that by finding a way to build a course

00:05:23.239 --> 00:05:25.720
or build a workshop around Pulsar Cloud,

00:05:25.720 --> 00:05:28.040
you're not only saving the time and effort

00:05:28.040 --> 00:05:30.200
of getting people in this unified environment,

00:05:30.200 --> 00:05:32.160
but you're able to bring people into this space

00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:34.000
where the system's going to scale with you.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:35.559
And if you have more students

00:05:35.559 --> 00:05:37.040
or if you have more instructors,

00:05:37.040 --> 00:05:39.279
they can kind of work into that flow as well.

00:05:40.640 --> 00:05:42.799
And when we're thinking about like,

00:05:42.799 --> 00:05:44.519
how do you go about and just deliver

00:05:44.519 --> 00:05:46.959
any kind of educational course,

00:05:46.959 --> 00:05:51.359
broadly speaking, it likely follows something like this.

00:05:51.359 --> 00:05:52.200
You're trying to set up

00:05:52.200 --> 00:05:54.040
with some kind of learning objectives.

00:05:54.040 --> 00:05:56.440
What do you hope to impart to students?

00:05:56.440 --> 00:05:59.040
What do you want the outcomes to be?

00:05:59.040 --> 00:06:01.239
Why do you believe that they're important?

00:06:01.239 --> 00:06:03.480
From that, you're putting together course material,

00:06:03.480 --> 00:06:06.160
what's going to put them on the best path

00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:09.920
to acquire, to achieve these learning objectives,

00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:13.040
getting into content distribution,

00:06:13.040 --> 00:06:16.000
being able to take a project or take some code

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:18.880
or just take a concept and put it in front of people

00:06:18.880 --> 00:06:20.440
at the right time.

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:22.559
And then finally, the ability to support

00:06:22.559 --> 00:06:24.399
and assess along the way.

00:06:24.399 --> 00:06:26.320
So, you know, was it effective?

00:06:26.320 --> 00:06:28.200
Where were the pain points?

00:06:28.200 --> 00:06:31.399
What individual issues came up that needed to have

00:06:31.399 --> 00:06:33.720
to be looked at a little bit more closely?

00:06:33.720 --> 00:06:34.880
So I'm curious, Minae, like,

00:06:34.880 --> 00:06:36.799
does this align with like your mental model

00:06:36.799 --> 00:06:38.920
as you're preparing courses,

00:06:38.920 --> 00:06:40.399
specifically data courses,

00:06:40.399 --> 00:06:41.600
which might be a little bit different

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:43.920
than teaching something that doesn't have a technical

00:06:43.920 --> 00:06:46.079
or a coding-based perspective?

00:06:47.480 --> 00:06:51.679
It aligns very well with the instructor I aspire to be.

00:06:51.679 --> 00:06:54.959
But I think that sometimes things go

00:06:54.959 --> 00:06:57.160
a little bit differently where I find myself

00:06:57.160 --> 00:07:00.440
sort of circling more than once through this,

00:07:00.440 --> 00:07:03.359
which is that, you know, creating course materials,

00:07:03.359 --> 00:07:05.480
that seems like the type of thing you should be doing

00:07:05.480 --> 00:07:07.640
at the beginning of the semester, for example.

00:07:07.640 --> 00:07:11.279
Like, however, for me, it's usually something

00:07:11.279 --> 00:07:14.040
that I'm doing throughout the semester.

00:07:14.040 --> 00:07:15.640
To be perfectly honest, at times,

00:07:15.640 --> 00:07:17.559
it's because I just don't have everything ready

00:07:17.559 --> 00:07:20.160
at the beginning, but also because sometimes, you know,

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:23.480
I read about a cool feature in a new released version

00:07:23.480 --> 00:07:25.920
of a package or something new with Corto.

00:07:25.920 --> 00:07:29.760
And what I want to do is I want to be able to show

00:07:29.760 --> 00:07:32.839
in class the next day, this new thing I've learned about.

00:07:32.839 --> 00:07:36.320
So that might mean that now I want, you know,

00:07:36.320 --> 00:07:40.320
the most recent version of a package to be installed

00:07:40.320 --> 00:07:41.880
on the environment where my students

00:07:41.880 --> 00:07:43.839
are going to be doing the computing.

00:07:43.839 --> 00:07:47.359
And to be able to have access to do that myself,

00:07:47.359 --> 00:07:50.880
as opposed to going through IT, has always been really nice.

00:07:50.880 --> 00:07:54.239
And also distributing content as well.

00:07:54.239 --> 00:07:56.160
You know, I don't necessarily have

00:07:56.160 --> 00:07:57.920
every single homework assignment,

00:07:57.920 --> 00:08:01.640
every single in-class exercise prepared and ready to go

00:08:01.640 --> 00:08:04.399
to be sort of like distributed at once to students.

00:08:04.399 --> 00:08:07.880
So usually these things unravel throughout the semester.

00:08:07.880 --> 00:08:11.119
I also find that students find it overwhelming

00:08:11.119 --> 00:08:13.000
to be delivered everything at once.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:16.079
And it allows me to pace things a little bit better

00:08:16.079 --> 00:08:17.799
based on how class went.

00:08:17.799 --> 00:08:22.359
So that flexibility of making things visible to students

00:08:22.359 --> 00:08:26.399
at a particular rate is another thing that I really like.

00:08:27.760 --> 00:08:31.239
Yeah, I'm curious, what courses are you typically teaching?

00:08:31.839 --> 00:08:33.640
We talk with a lot of people that are teaching psychology

00:08:33.640 --> 00:08:36.719
or economics or statistics or getting into data science.

00:08:36.719 --> 00:08:38.119
Where is your focus?

00:08:39.280 --> 00:08:43.080
So I am a faculty in the statistics department.

00:08:43.080 --> 00:08:47.000
My primary focus for teaching is introductory education.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:48.719
So that's introductory statistics

00:08:48.719 --> 00:08:50.359
or introduction to data science.

00:08:50.359 --> 00:08:53.559
The courses I've taught most regularly, most recently,

00:08:53.559 --> 00:08:55.440
have been introduction to data science

00:08:55.440 --> 00:08:57.760
using the data science in a box curriculum.

00:08:57.760 --> 00:09:00.599
But I also teach data visualization courses,

00:09:00.599 --> 00:09:03.679
both at the introductory and advanced level as well.

00:09:03.679 --> 00:09:05.559
I teach a few other things here and there too,

00:09:05.559 --> 00:09:08.440
but these have been sort of like the ones

00:09:08.440 --> 00:09:09.919
that I teach most regularly,

00:09:09.919 --> 00:09:12.479
and usually quite large classes.

00:09:13.640 --> 00:09:16.559
What is quite large from your point of view?

00:09:16.559 --> 00:09:19.599
Well, next semester it will be almost 300 students.

00:09:19.599 --> 00:09:23.520
So that's large for my university, yeah.

00:09:23.520 --> 00:09:25.679
Yeah, yeah, fantastic.

00:09:25.679 --> 00:09:27.640
Yeah, digging in a little bit to these themes

00:09:27.640 --> 00:09:29.200
a little bit more.

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:30.960
So starting out with the learning objectives.

00:09:30.960 --> 00:09:32.840
One of the courses that I taught years ago

00:09:32.840 --> 00:09:34.799
was just this data literacy type course,

00:09:34.799 --> 00:09:35.880
data as a second language.

00:09:35.880 --> 00:09:37.400
So I knew I had three units, right?

00:09:37.400 --> 00:09:39.479
I wanted people to understand what data is.

00:09:39.479 --> 00:09:41.119
I wanted them to be able to manipulate it

00:09:41.119 --> 00:09:42.960
in more sophisticated ways.

00:09:42.960 --> 00:09:44.320
Then I also wanted them to be able to go out

00:09:44.320 --> 00:09:46.400
and communicate to other people.

00:09:46.400 --> 00:09:47.239
So when thinking through,

00:09:47.239 --> 00:09:50.080
once I had that bad experience trying to do things

00:09:50.080 --> 00:09:53.280
with everybody on their own laptops,

00:09:53.280 --> 00:09:56.119
I moved into what could PositCloud kind of like deliver

00:09:56.119 --> 00:09:58.400
and how could I take some of this content

00:09:58.400 --> 00:10:00.000
and put it into some of the functions

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:03.000
and features on PositCloud?

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:04.239
So the first part was,

00:10:04.239 --> 00:10:06.599
what can I teach within RStudio IDE?

00:10:06.599 --> 00:10:09.400
Later PositCloud has added Jupyter Notebook,

00:10:09.400 --> 00:10:11.239
which is still in a beta,

00:10:11.239 --> 00:10:12.760
but for those instructors who do wanna have

00:10:12.760 --> 00:10:16.000
some native Python coding material,

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:17.640
they can do it through that.

00:10:17.640 --> 00:10:20.159
And then where am I gonna get my data examples?

00:10:20.159 --> 00:10:22.159
How are they gonna be brought into the system?

00:10:22.159 --> 00:10:25.719
Are we gonna go out and just import CSV files?

00:10:25.719 --> 00:10:28.960
More recently, PositCloud added data connections this year,

00:10:28.960 --> 00:10:31.760
which makes it easier to connect to databases,

00:10:31.760 --> 00:10:34.640
which from what I understand are not often taught

00:10:34.640 --> 00:10:35.840
in a lot of data courses,

00:10:35.840 --> 00:10:38.840
especially at the undergrad level

00:10:39.760 --> 00:10:41.000
in terms of just connecting

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:43.119
and be able to start doing manipulation.

00:10:43.119 --> 00:10:46.359
But we found some really great public databases

00:10:46.359 --> 00:10:47.599
that are out there that allow you

00:10:47.599 --> 00:10:50.320
like to put in a Postgres connection,

00:10:50.320 --> 00:10:52.880
make that connection and start performing analysis on it,

00:10:52.880 --> 00:10:54.239
which is great.

00:10:55.799 --> 00:10:58.080
Mene, are you typically working with flat files

00:10:58.080 --> 00:10:58.919
at this point?

00:10:58.919 --> 00:11:01.039
Are you using data files from within packages?

00:11:01.039 --> 00:11:02.599
What is your go-to source?

00:11:03.599 --> 00:11:05.679
Mostly flat files.

00:11:05.679 --> 00:11:08.280
We start with data files from packages.

00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:13.039
So my teaching style is that the first thing we teach

00:11:13.039 --> 00:11:14.760
is data visualization.

00:11:14.760 --> 00:11:17.440
So we sort of start by visualizing data

00:11:17.440 --> 00:11:21.119
that is already, not necessarily I would say cleaned up,

00:11:21.119 --> 00:11:22.840
but in a data frame format, let's say.

00:11:22.840 --> 00:11:25.760
So already in R, the variable types

00:11:25.760 --> 00:11:28.760
are what you expect them to be like factors

00:11:28.760 --> 00:11:30.119
or dates and stuff like that.

00:11:30.119 --> 00:11:33.440
So that's why we start with data sets and packages.

00:11:33.440 --> 00:11:36.440
And then we take a step back and import data

00:11:36.440 --> 00:11:40.039
primarily from flat files.

00:11:40.039 --> 00:11:43.440
So Excel or CSV files or Google Sheets

00:11:43.440 --> 00:11:46.239
is another one that we tend to import data from.

00:11:46.239 --> 00:11:48.599
I don't teach databases much,

00:11:48.599 --> 00:11:51.799
but another thing we do teach is web scraping.

00:11:51.799 --> 00:11:53.239
So then in that case,

00:11:53.239 --> 00:11:55.760
the data is coming from an unstructured source

00:11:55.760 --> 00:11:59.719
and then using code getting structured into a data frame.

00:11:59.719 --> 00:12:00.719
Yeah.

00:12:00.719 --> 00:12:01.559
Yeah, great.

00:12:01.559 --> 00:12:03.919
And then bringing this into what the course

00:12:03.919 --> 00:12:05.119
would look like in PositCloud.

00:12:05.119 --> 00:12:06.599
PositCloud I think is powerful

00:12:06.599 --> 00:12:07.919
from an educational point of view

00:12:07.919 --> 00:12:10.479
because it's based around this notion of a space.

00:12:10.479 --> 00:12:12.359
So you create a count as we're gonna see

00:12:12.359 --> 00:12:13.599
in a demo in a few minutes.

00:12:13.599 --> 00:12:16.000
You're able to create this dedicated space.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:17.640
You can use it for whatever you want.

00:12:17.640 --> 00:12:20.000
You can bring in specific people.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:21.599
So when thinking through it from the point

00:12:22.359 --> 00:12:24.000
of view of bringing in course materials,

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:26.520
you can make a space, you can bring in new projects,

00:12:26.520 --> 00:12:29.280
you can create RStudio projects or Jupyter projects.

00:12:29.280 --> 00:12:32.640
You can now publish some outputs as well to the space.

00:12:32.640 --> 00:12:34.559
If you have Quarto, let's say,

00:12:34.559 --> 00:12:37.280
maybe summarizing the semester's content.

00:12:37.280 --> 00:12:38.479
And then once you do this,

00:12:38.479 --> 00:12:40.159
you're able to manage all the content

00:12:40.159 --> 00:12:43.559
that you have within this given contained environment.

00:12:43.559 --> 00:12:44.640
So once you have it there,

00:12:44.640 --> 00:12:46.640
you wanna go out and be able to put it

00:12:46.640 --> 00:12:48.080
in the hands of students.

00:12:48.080 --> 00:12:49.799
So there are a couple of ways we'll look at

00:12:49.799 --> 00:12:53.479
where you can invite students to your space directly,

00:12:53.479 --> 00:12:56.599
controlling what they are able and not able to do,

00:12:56.599 --> 00:12:57.880
and then what they are able

00:12:57.880 --> 00:13:00.159
and not able to see at different moments.

00:13:00.159 --> 00:13:01.320
So Meena mentioned earlier,

00:13:01.320 --> 00:13:02.760
like not overwhelming students

00:13:02.760 --> 00:13:05.000
and throwing up every single thing from the semester.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:07.280
We have some features on Positive Cloud

00:13:07.280 --> 00:13:09.000
that can make that easier as well.

00:13:10.599 --> 00:13:11.760
And then at the end of all this,

00:13:11.760 --> 00:13:14.280
like once you have students that are in the space,

00:13:14.280 --> 00:13:16.080
they're able to access your content

00:13:16.080 --> 00:13:19.359
and go along and learn kind of in real time with you,

00:13:19.960 --> 00:13:21.000
your ability as an instructor

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:22.960
to go into a student's project,

00:13:22.960 --> 00:13:24.320
be able to run the code,

00:13:24.320 --> 00:13:25.760
maybe see what is going wrong,

00:13:25.760 --> 00:13:29.400
potentially fix issues or work collaboratively,

00:13:29.400 --> 00:13:30.719
make comments.

00:13:30.719 --> 00:13:32.559
And then at the end of all this,

00:13:32.559 --> 00:13:33.400
we were talking about,

00:13:33.400 --> 00:13:36.320
how do we assess and evaluate work?

00:13:36.320 --> 00:13:38.679
And I know that we don't have actually

00:13:38.679 --> 00:13:41.080
built in functionality right now on Positive Cloud

00:13:41.080 --> 00:13:44.679
to really support the grading aspect of things.

00:13:44.679 --> 00:13:45.520
So I'm curious, Meena,

00:13:45.520 --> 00:13:47.559
in all these courses that you've taught over the years,

00:13:47.559 --> 00:13:52.039
like what is your process for evaluating,

00:13:52.039 --> 00:13:55.119
learning outcomes from this type of material?

00:13:56.320 --> 00:13:59.960
So usually it really depends on

00:13:59.960 --> 00:14:01.159
the course that I'm teaching.

00:14:01.159 --> 00:14:03.159
In my Intro Stat courses,

00:14:03.919 --> 00:14:05.799
what we, the evaluation,

00:14:05.799 --> 00:14:07.760
actually in any of the courses I teach,

00:14:07.760 --> 00:14:11.880
the evaluation itself happens outside of Positive Cloud.

00:14:11.880 --> 00:14:14.080
And so students submitted using

00:14:14.080 --> 00:14:16.599
whatever course management system we're using.

00:14:16.599 --> 00:14:18.960
So in my Introductory Statistics course,

00:14:18.960 --> 00:14:22.440
that is happening on Gradescope, for example.

00:14:22.440 --> 00:14:26.400
So they render their Quarto document to a PDF file

00:14:26.400 --> 00:14:30.320
that they then export out of that Positive Cloud project.

00:14:30.320 --> 00:14:32.760
And then they upload it to Gradescope.

00:14:32.760 --> 00:14:35.039
And that's where the grading is happening basically.

00:14:35.039 --> 00:14:38.440
And feedback is being given there as well.

00:14:38.440 --> 00:14:41.520
With my Intro Data Science courses,

00:14:41.520 --> 00:14:44.760
there is also a Git and GitHub component to the course.

00:14:44.760 --> 00:14:45.679
So in that case,

00:14:45.679 --> 00:14:48.919
everything is submitted as a GitHub repository

00:14:48.919 --> 00:14:52.159
and the evaluation, depending on the course,

00:14:52.159 --> 00:14:56.039
is either done there or on Gradescope as well.

00:14:56.039 --> 00:14:57.359
The way we've been,

00:14:57.359 --> 00:15:00.239
like for the courses where I teach Positive Cloud,

00:15:00.239 --> 00:15:03.400
the way it has come into play has been more on the,

00:15:03.400 --> 00:15:05.320
sort of the support side,

00:15:05.320 --> 00:15:07.960
the go into a, like not the assessment side,

00:15:07.960 --> 00:15:09.000
but the support side,

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:14.000
being able to sort of go in and diagnose for the students

00:15:14.080 --> 00:15:15.719
what the issue might be.

00:15:15.719 --> 00:15:19.080
And I will say that that's usually not like a first thing

00:15:19.080 --> 00:15:21.880
I offer to the students.

00:15:21.880 --> 00:15:23.159
You know, if we're,

00:15:23.159 --> 00:15:27.359
even if we're physically together in office hours,

00:15:27.359 --> 00:15:28.559
but also if we're not,

00:15:28.559 --> 00:15:31.679
and we're talking on like a course discussion forum

00:15:31.679 --> 00:15:32.520
or something,

00:15:32.520 --> 00:15:35.400
I try to get them to articulate what the issue is.

00:15:35.400 --> 00:15:37.359
But sometimes it turns out

00:15:37.359 --> 00:15:39.880
that we're not getting anywhere with that.

00:15:39.880 --> 00:15:41.760
And the student is getting more frustrated

00:15:41.760 --> 00:15:43.960
because they sort of don't have the right terms

00:15:43.960 --> 00:15:45.799
and I can't see what they're doing.

00:15:45.799 --> 00:15:49.280
And maybe they're not sharing like a full screenshot with me

00:15:49.280 --> 00:15:50.280
of what's happening.

00:15:50.280 --> 00:15:52.960
So being able to just peek in,

00:15:52.960 --> 00:15:55.799
not necessarily always to fix the issues,

00:15:55.799 --> 00:15:57.840
but to understand what the issue is

00:15:57.840 --> 00:16:00.880
and then leave the space and then articulate to them,

00:16:00.880 --> 00:16:03.760
here is what you might want to look into.

00:16:03.760 --> 00:16:05.239
It's really, really nice.

00:16:06.119 --> 00:16:07.919
Yeah, that's great advice.

00:16:07.919 --> 00:16:09.239
What I'd like to do now,

00:16:09.239 --> 00:16:11.960
before we get into a live demo,

00:16:11.960 --> 00:16:13.559
is just talk a little bit about the two ways

00:16:13.559 --> 00:16:15.320
that you might be able to set up

00:16:15.320 --> 00:16:18.479
instructor style accounts on Paws of Cloud.

00:16:18.479 --> 00:16:20.599
If you are like an individual instructor

00:16:20.599 --> 00:16:22.359
or you are running workshops,

00:16:22.359 --> 00:16:24.280
you know, you can create an individual account.

00:16:24.280 --> 00:16:26.359
You can go up and if you have five different courses,

00:16:26.359 --> 00:16:27.840
you can make five different spaces,

00:16:27.840 --> 00:16:30.119
or you can use one space and reuse it for different groups

00:16:30.119 --> 00:16:32.359
and cohorts of students that are coming through.

00:16:32.359 --> 00:16:35.559
If you are part of a wider group within your institution

00:16:35.559 --> 00:16:37.200
or your university,

00:16:37.200 --> 00:16:39.000
we have organizational accounts

00:16:39.760 --> 00:16:41.280
where there can be sort of central management

00:16:41.280 --> 00:16:42.960
of the instructors that you would like

00:16:42.960 --> 00:16:44.440
to be a part of that.

00:16:44.440 --> 00:16:46.000
So this means like centralized billing

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:47.640
and also the ability to sort of monitor

00:16:47.640 --> 00:16:51.640
and see who's doing what in which space.

00:16:51.640 --> 00:16:53.200
So what I would like to do now

00:16:53.200 --> 00:16:56.520
is hop over to Paws of Cloud.

00:16:56.520 --> 00:16:59.719
So I'm gonna switch into the browser here

00:16:59.719 --> 00:17:01.280
and I'm gonna go ahead and log in

00:17:01.280 --> 00:17:02.320
and we'll start just by looking

00:17:02.320 --> 00:17:05.280
at the individual approach to doing this.

00:17:05.280 --> 00:17:06.160
And what I always encourage,

00:17:06.160 --> 00:17:07.959
like if you're new on this call

00:17:07.959 --> 00:17:10.680
and you haven't been in Paws of Cloud yet,

00:17:10.680 --> 00:17:13.119
there are free accounts that are available

00:17:13.119 --> 00:17:15.079
and it's the best way to sort of experience

00:17:15.079 --> 00:17:17.479
and feel what Paws of Cloud is like

00:17:17.479 --> 00:17:19.800
because we don't get a lot of this functionality

00:17:19.800 --> 00:17:22.280
by different tiers of service.

00:17:22.280 --> 00:17:25.040
Like if you were to have a paid plan eventually,

00:17:25.040 --> 00:17:26.719
you would have like more compute hours

00:17:26.719 --> 00:17:28.920
and you'd have more compute power,

00:17:28.920 --> 00:17:31.160
but all the things, all the building blocks

00:17:31.160 --> 00:17:33.839
such as spaces and projects are gonna be there

00:17:33.839 --> 00:17:35.959
on a free account as well.

00:17:35.959 --> 00:17:38.400
So let me go ahead and log in now.

00:17:38.400 --> 00:17:40.560
And the first time that you get into Paws of Cloud,

00:17:40.560 --> 00:17:43.599
you're gonna get to a relatively plain page

00:17:43.599 --> 00:17:45.439
that is known as your workspace.

00:17:45.439 --> 00:17:47.839
And here you could start building projects

00:17:47.839 --> 00:17:50.119
and you could see the specific project

00:17:50.119 --> 00:17:51.680
that you might be working on,

00:17:51.680 --> 00:17:53.199
but what you can't do in this first space

00:17:53.199 --> 00:17:55.479
is invite others to collaborate with you.

00:17:55.479 --> 00:17:58.040
And of course, we're looking at education here.

00:17:58.040 --> 00:17:59.239
So we want to have students,

00:17:59.239 --> 00:18:02.199
we wanna have a back and forth of our content.

00:18:02.199 --> 00:18:05.040
And for this, we're gonna go to this notion of space.

00:18:05.079 --> 00:18:07.640
So if I click on the end and I scroll down,

00:18:07.640 --> 00:18:10.000
I can create a new space.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:12.959
And maybe we call this stat 250.

00:18:12.959 --> 00:18:14.479
Most people won't have a dropdown here,

00:18:14.479 --> 00:18:16.359
but if you have multiple accounts you can access,

00:18:16.359 --> 00:18:17.599
you can choose one here.

00:18:17.599 --> 00:18:20.760
I'm gonna go to my individual personal account

00:18:20.760 --> 00:18:22.199
and just create this space.

00:18:23.160 --> 00:18:25.800
So we have a new course area.

00:18:25.800 --> 00:18:28.199
You can see that two new tabs popped up.

00:18:28.199 --> 00:18:29.599
I have both data,

00:18:29.599 --> 00:18:32.079
which are these data connections that I mentioned earlier.

00:18:32.079 --> 00:18:34.119
So if you do work into your curriculum,

00:18:34.119 --> 00:18:37.199
some ability to go out and touch a real database,

00:18:37.199 --> 00:18:38.839
you can set up the credentials here

00:18:38.839 --> 00:18:41.520
so that students don't need to be entering these themselves

00:18:41.520 --> 00:18:43.319
over and over again.

00:18:43.319 --> 00:18:45.839
But more importantly, we have this member tab.

00:18:45.839 --> 00:18:47.319
And here's where we're gonna be able

00:18:47.319 --> 00:18:48.680
to have a couple of different ways

00:18:48.680 --> 00:18:50.959
to bring in different people into our space

00:18:50.959 --> 00:18:52.479
to engage with our content.

00:18:53.520 --> 00:18:55.680
And we'll do that in a few moments.

00:18:55.680 --> 00:18:56.520
But first of all,

00:18:56.520 --> 00:18:58.040
let's start off with like the core functionality, right?

00:18:58.040 --> 00:19:00.199
You see this dropdown new project.

00:19:00.199 --> 00:19:02.719
If I click on this, I see four options.

00:19:02.719 --> 00:19:05.640
I can either create a project from a template.

00:19:05.640 --> 00:19:07.319
And if I were to do this,

00:19:07.319 --> 00:19:09.119
you're gonna see a few things.

00:19:09.959 --> 00:19:11.800
First, you're gonna see that we don't have a template

00:19:11.800 --> 00:19:14.319
defined specifically for our new space yet.

00:19:14.319 --> 00:19:15.160
We could do that,

00:19:15.160 --> 00:19:17.719
and we'll do that in a few moments time.

00:19:17.719 --> 00:19:20.680
Or you could create a new project from a template

00:19:20.680 --> 00:19:23.359
that really Posit has put together for you.

00:19:23.359 --> 00:19:25.079
So for instance,

00:19:25.079 --> 00:19:27.479
we have data analysis in R with a tidyverse.

00:19:27.479 --> 00:19:28.719
If you were to go into that,

00:19:28.719 --> 00:19:31.599
you'd be able to see a markdown document

00:19:31.599 --> 00:19:33.359
that talks through different functionality

00:19:33.359 --> 00:19:36.680
within the tidyverse for basic exploratory analysis.

00:19:36.680 --> 00:19:37.680
And all the packages,

00:19:37.680 --> 00:19:39.920
all the data that you would need for those examples

00:19:39.920 --> 00:19:42.439
would already be included in there.

00:19:42.439 --> 00:19:45.199
But the most common thing I think teachers do,

00:19:45.199 --> 00:19:47.920
they go through and they create a new RStudio project.

00:19:49.800 --> 00:19:54.280
And maybe this will be called week one EDA,

00:19:54.280 --> 00:19:56.560
depending on what we're teaching.

00:19:56.560 --> 00:19:58.880
It's going to take about 15 to 20 seconds

00:19:58.880 --> 00:20:00.719
to go ahead and spin up a new instance

00:20:00.719 --> 00:20:03.000
specifically for your project.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:04.599
And then once you're in it,

00:20:04.599 --> 00:20:07.880
I would say 90, 95% of what you'd expect

00:20:07.880 --> 00:20:10.239
on RStudio IDE on your desktop,

00:20:10.239 --> 00:20:14.439
you'd be able to achieve and accomplish here as well.

00:20:14.439 --> 00:20:16.479
So you can go ahead and upload files

00:20:16.479 --> 00:20:18.439
from your local environment.

00:20:18.439 --> 00:20:21.079
You can make those database connections

00:20:21.079 --> 00:20:23.319
either through the ones that we defined earlier

00:20:23.319 --> 00:20:24.280
through Posit Cloud,

00:20:24.280 --> 00:20:26.479
or a new one through other database drivers

00:20:26.479 --> 00:20:28.760
that happen to be available.

00:20:28.800 --> 00:20:31.839
We could build in markdown files, code.

00:20:31.839 --> 00:20:34.319
Again, we can bring in data to support all of this

00:20:34.319 --> 00:20:37.359
and essentially building up what you want in week one

00:20:37.359 --> 00:20:40.040
for your students to be able to engage with.

00:20:41.680 --> 00:20:43.040
I also won't publish anything here,

00:20:43.040 --> 00:20:45.160
but I'll show you the functionality we have as well.

00:20:45.160 --> 00:20:47.199
So maybe you're working with a Shiny app.

00:20:50.359 --> 00:20:54.880
What we can do is build up the Shiny app.

00:20:54.880 --> 00:20:58.439
And we'll just look at the base one that comes included.

00:20:59.359 --> 00:21:03.520
We're gonna have to go out and get all the packages first.

00:21:03.520 --> 00:21:05.719
And that's what it's downloading right now.

00:21:07.199 --> 00:21:08.839
And then once that is complete,

00:21:09.800 --> 00:21:13.359
I'm gonna go ahead and call this test.

00:21:15.239 --> 00:21:17.479
Gonna make sure that when we run this app,

00:21:17.479 --> 00:21:18.520
we're gonna do it in our window

00:21:18.520 --> 00:21:20.479
so we can see it within the pane.

00:21:23.400 --> 00:21:27.560
So we can see right away our interactive Shiny application.

00:21:27.560 --> 00:21:29.920
And because we're all part of this same

00:21:29.920 --> 00:21:32.079
unified experience on PositCloud,

00:21:32.079 --> 00:21:34.560
if I wanted to publish this to my space

00:21:34.560 --> 00:21:37.560
for other students to see, you could do that.

00:21:37.560 --> 00:21:38.920
So again, we're just gonna go ahead

00:21:38.920 --> 00:21:41.040
and install the required packages

00:21:41.040 --> 00:21:44.640
to make this publication publish to PositCloud.

00:21:44.640 --> 00:21:48.040
And you can see by default where it's asking you to go

00:21:48.040 --> 00:21:50.079
is to the space that we're putting it in.

00:21:50.079 --> 00:21:51.439
So we won't do that now,

00:21:51.439 --> 00:21:54.719
but if we did and we go back to our content list,

00:21:54.719 --> 00:21:57.760
we would see both the project that we just created,

00:21:57.760 --> 00:22:00.400
the week one EDA, and we would see the project.

00:22:01.520 --> 00:22:04.000
Now at the moment, we're missing two key components

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:05.719
to teaching a course, right?

00:22:05.719 --> 00:22:08.160
We're missing students to look at things.

00:22:08.160 --> 00:22:10.079
And we're also missing the ability for students

00:22:10.079 --> 00:22:13.680
who might be here to see what you worked on.

00:22:13.680 --> 00:22:15.400
So this first RStudio project,

00:22:15.400 --> 00:22:17.400
if you wanted to put that in the hands of students

00:22:17.400 --> 00:22:20.000
in your space, you can see that it's marked private.

00:22:21.239 --> 00:22:23.239
We're gonna go into settings

00:22:23.239 --> 00:22:25.280
and we're gonna go to access.

00:22:25.280 --> 00:22:29.319
We're gonna change that private to space members.

00:22:29.319 --> 00:22:31.319
So that's the first thing that you would do

00:22:31.319 --> 00:22:33.280
to put the content in front of students

00:22:33.280 --> 00:22:34.800
that are in the space.

00:22:34.800 --> 00:22:36.400
And then we have two options here

00:22:36.400 --> 00:22:39.959
that can be very relevant, I think, when teaching a course.

00:22:39.959 --> 00:22:43.160
The first is making this project an assignment.

00:22:43.160 --> 00:22:45.040
And if I were to click on this,

00:22:45.040 --> 00:22:47.280
you can see that there is an assignment button

00:22:47.280 --> 00:22:50.920
that comes with that week one EDA.

00:22:50.920 --> 00:22:53.319
And now when a student were to join the space,

00:22:53.319 --> 00:22:55.800
they would come in and it would change.

00:22:55.800 --> 00:22:57.439
For them, they would see start.

00:22:57.439 --> 00:22:59.079
So they know that there's an action on it.

00:22:59.079 --> 00:23:00.239
They would click start.

00:23:00.239 --> 00:23:03.119
It would make a copy of the project specifically for them

00:23:03.119 --> 00:23:05.280
that then they could interact with

00:23:05.280 --> 00:23:07.880
without risking what you put together in your first one.

00:23:07.880 --> 00:23:09.560
It's a safe environment that they can go back

00:23:09.560 --> 00:23:11.640
and they can create it again and again and again

00:23:11.640 --> 00:23:12.640
if they wanted to.

00:23:13.520 --> 00:23:15.079
We also have the ability now

00:23:15.079 --> 00:23:16.760
with a new feature called templates

00:23:16.760 --> 00:23:20.119
to turn this into a specific template for the space.

00:23:20.119 --> 00:23:21.880
So if I click on template,

00:23:21.880 --> 00:23:24.959
it's gonna take away the assignment functionality.

00:23:24.959 --> 00:23:26.920
I can make this template something

00:23:26.920 --> 00:23:28.760
that we can get from that initial list

00:23:28.760 --> 00:23:31.040
of start a new project with templates.

00:23:31.040 --> 00:23:32.359
I can also make it the default

00:23:32.359 --> 00:23:36.479
for every single RStudio project that comes from this space.

00:23:37.599 --> 00:23:39.959
Let's just go ahead and save it as template

00:23:39.959 --> 00:23:42.760
just to show you where this would now pop up.

