00:23:58.959 --> 00:24:00.560
Another example of using templates

00:24:00.560 --> 00:24:02.560
may be to like surface like all the data sets

00:24:02.560 --> 00:24:05.119
you wanna be able to share out throughout a semester.

00:24:05.119 --> 00:24:06.839
And if a student wants to create a new project

00:24:06.839 --> 00:24:08.319
from those core data sets,

00:24:08.319 --> 00:24:11.040
they could again come back and back to this template.

00:24:11.920 --> 00:24:15.000
Minnie, I'm curious when you're setting up courses

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:16.400
on Posit Cloud,

00:24:16.400 --> 00:24:18.359
are you typically using assignments

00:24:18.359 --> 00:24:20.640
or templates or nothing at all?

00:24:21.520 --> 00:24:24.000
Both, so I definitely use a template

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:27.160
particularly because there's a,

00:24:27.160 --> 00:24:30.160
I always use the Tidyverse packages

00:24:30.160 --> 00:24:31.319
and I like being able to,

00:24:31.319 --> 00:24:33.439
I teach with library Tidyverse.

00:24:33.439 --> 00:24:34.800
I wanna make sure that we have

00:24:34.800 --> 00:24:37.280
all of the Tidyverse packages installed,

00:24:37.280 --> 00:24:38.719
even if for a given lesson,

00:24:38.719 --> 00:24:40.920
we may not be using all of them.

00:24:40.920 --> 00:24:42.640
And so that's one of the things

00:24:42.640 --> 00:24:45.239
I put in my template for sure.

00:24:45.239 --> 00:24:50.199
And also, rendering a Quarto document with our code

00:24:50.199 --> 00:24:52.640
and that requires like Knitter to be installed and stuff.

00:24:52.640 --> 00:24:54.359
So I make sure that all of that

00:24:54.359 --> 00:24:55.959
is installed in the template.

00:24:55.959 --> 00:24:58.359
So that's the first thing I set.

00:24:58.359 --> 00:25:01.319
And every once in a while throughout the semester,

00:25:01.319 --> 00:25:03.319
I'll update the template too.

00:25:03.319 --> 00:25:07.000
So that going forward, like we use the new packages,

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:09.920
but usually that stays for the semester.

00:25:09.920 --> 00:25:13.119
And then for each day that I teach,

00:25:13.119 --> 00:25:14.239
so this semester I'm teaching

00:25:14.239 --> 00:25:16.199
an introductory statistics course

00:25:16.199 --> 00:25:17.760
where we're using Posit Cloud.

00:25:17.760 --> 00:25:21.119
And every single day we have

00:25:21.119 --> 00:25:22.800
an application exercise in the class.

00:25:22.800 --> 00:25:24.400
So that's like a live coding thing.

00:25:24.400 --> 00:25:27.199
So I have stubs of code that I share

00:25:27.199 --> 00:25:29.599
with the students in a Quarto document.

00:25:29.599 --> 00:25:31.920
And then we sort of improve upon them

00:25:31.920 --> 00:25:33.959
during the in-class exercises.

00:25:33.959 --> 00:25:36.880
Those are set as assignments

00:25:36.880 --> 00:25:40.199
and I make them visible sort of shortly before class.

00:25:40.199 --> 00:25:42.280
And then their homework assignments

00:25:42.319 --> 00:25:45.359
and stuff are also distributed as assignments.

00:25:45.359 --> 00:25:49.880
What I like is that it nicely contains them for the students.

00:25:49.880 --> 00:25:54.880
So in my opinion, it's sort of almost an improvement

00:25:55.640 --> 00:25:58.920
above working with the IDE for learners

00:25:58.920 --> 00:26:01.719
because the idea of switching between projects

00:26:01.719 --> 00:26:04.400
in the local IDE is I think something

00:26:04.400 --> 00:26:08.400
that comes with experience versus in Posit Cloud

00:26:08.400 --> 00:26:11.599
to switch between like different sets of documents.

00:26:11.599 --> 00:26:13.199
You have to switch the projects.

00:26:13.199 --> 00:26:15.000
So I feel like it teaches you

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:19.079
to think about projects earlier than you might otherwise

00:26:19.079 --> 00:26:21.160
which is I think a benefit.

00:26:21.160 --> 00:26:23.199
Yeah, yeah, I think you're right.

