At this point, I'd like to invite back on Hannah,

00:37:22.520 --> 00:37:25.159
who's on our side and is gonna help with the Q&A

00:37:25.159 --> 00:37:26.000
that's come on the board

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:28.760
as we've been going through the presentation.

00:37:28.760 --> 00:37:29.840
Hey, thank you.

00:37:29.840 --> 00:37:30.679
Thanks, Alex.

00:37:30.679 --> 00:37:31.520
Thanks, Mine.

00:37:32.719 --> 00:37:34.280
Yeah, like Alex said, I'm Hannah.

00:37:34.280 --> 00:37:35.719
I'm on the marketing team here at posit.

00:37:35.719 --> 00:37:37.959
So I'm just gonna moderate some of the questions

00:37:37.959 --> 00:37:39.879
that have been coming in today.

00:37:39.879 --> 00:37:41.959
And just a reminder, if you still have questions,

00:37:41.959 --> 00:37:44.679
we've got a chunk of time here at the end to answer them.

00:37:44.679 --> 00:37:47.000
So feel free to keep on submitting questions

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:50.280
and we'll just run through them as we receive them.

00:37:50.280 --> 00:37:54.040
But the first question that I would like to ask you both

00:37:54.040 --> 00:37:55.280
is from Sanjay.

00:37:55.280 --> 00:37:57.639
And he asked, if you were asked the top reason

00:37:57.639 --> 00:38:00.120
for what you like about posit.cloud,

00:38:00.120 --> 00:38:01.719
what would be your response?

00:38:02.840 --> 00:38:04.639
I think Mine should answer this one.

00:38:06.919 --> 00:38:10.639
So I think I have, the top reason I would say

00:38:10.639 --> 00:38:14.040
is being able to peek into student projects so easily.

00:38:14.040 --> 00:38:16.280
I think that feels like a superpower.

00:38:16.280 --> 00:38:19.520
Even when you're not with them, you can do this.

00:38:19.520 --> 00:38:22.800
This was incredibly helpful when we were teaching

00:38:22.800 --> 00:38:24.919
fully virtually a couple of years ago,

00:38:24.919 --> 00:38:26.639
but I still find it very useful

00:38:26.639 --> 00:38:29.679
even though teaching is happening in person.

00:38:29.679 --> 00:38:32.080
But I have to add that second reason,

00:38:32.080 --> 00:38:33.879
which is the fact that everything

00:38:33.879 --> 00:38:35.919
is like a contained project.

00:38:35.919 --> 00:38:40.919
So students don't have to worry about sort of file paths

00:38:41.199 --> 00:38:43.360
and where they put their files.

00:38:43.360 --> 00:38:45.639
You set up the file structure for them

00:38:45.639 --> 00:38:47.120
and they start computing in there,

00:38:47.120 --> 00:38:51.600
which I find to be very helpful for new learners

00:38:51.600 --> 00:38:54.439
as opposed to sort of bogging them down

00:38:54.479 --> 00:38:57.479
with those details as well on day one of class.

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:01.280
Yeah, the only thing I would add is the flexibility

00:39:01.280 --> 00:39:04.639
of spinning up new courses, of adding and removing students.

00:39:04.639 --> 00:39:07.159
Like it makes it very easy to sort of build that cohort

00:39:07.159 --> 00:39:08.439
that you want to see the content

00:39:08.439 --> 00:39:10.399
that you're putting together.

00:39:10.399 --> 00:39:13.000
Yeah, that's super helpful.

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:15.199
Next question I'll go to.

00:39:16.639 --> 00:39:19.760
When I share with my students a project all installed,

00:39:19.760 --> 00:39:21.800
our packages are available to them,

00:39:21.800 --> 00:39:24.919
but that does not seem to be the case with Python packages.

00:39:24.919 --> 00:39:27.600
Is that really the case or is there something else?

00:39:28.679 --> 00:39:31.000
I think if you're using Jupyter Notebooks,

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:32.239
the best thing that you can do

00:39:32.239 --> 00:39:34.679
is to set up through the templating functionality

00:39:34.679 --> 00:39:35.520
that we looked at.

00:39:35.520 --> 00:39:37.639
So for sure using that templating functionality,

00:39:37.639 --> 00:39:39.719
you start a new Jupyter Notebook project,

00:39:39.719 --> 00:39:42.239
you bring in all the packages that you want to.

00:39:42.239 --> 00:39:44.080
And then if you set that as a template,

00:39:44.080 --> 00:39:46.159
your students are gonna be able to access that project

00:39:46.159 --> 00:39:48.800
with all those pre-installed packages that are there.

00:39:49.800 --> 00:39:50.639
Awesome.

00:39:51.840 --> 00:39:54.399
And then I think you answered the next question.

00:39:54.399 --> 00:39:57.239
So I'll skip that one and go to this one.

00:39:57.239 --> 00:40:00.199
Is it possible to publish on PositCloud,

00:40:00.199 --> 00:40:03.919
say an HTML document generated from a Cordo Notebook

00:40:03.919 --> 00:40:05.560
that can be shared publicly

00:40:05.560 --> 00:40:08.280
and anyone with the link can access it?

00:40:08.280 --> 00:40:10.159
At this point, no.

00:40:10.159 --> 00:40:12.280
All sharing on PositCloud has to go

00:40:12.280 --> 00:40:14.280
either to somebody within your space

00:40:14.280 --> 00:40:17.000
or to another person that has a PositCloud account.

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:18.840
Okay.

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:23.280
Next question from Ralph is,

00:40:23.280 --> 00:40:26.719
if students want to access their work after a workshop,

00:40:26.719 --> 00:40:29.439
I conduct corporate training for other companies.

00:40:29.439 --> 00:40:32.000
What are the options besides just keeping them

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:33.879
as a student in perpetuity?

00:40:35.080 --> 00:40:37.120
Mindy, how do you handle a sort of content transfer

00:40:37.120 --> 00:40:38.239
during your courses?

00:40:39.840 --> 00:40:42.679
So I think one of two things.

00:40:42.879 --> 00:40:47.879
Some students can choose to transfer that project

00:40:48.879 --> 00:40:52.439
into their own workspace so they can move it.

00:40:53.560 --> 00:40:55.600
More often, I also have students

00:40:55.600 --> 00:40:59.159
who just export the project out like locally.

00:40:59.159 --> 00:41:02.879
So they make sort of a local folder of all of their work,

00:41:02.879 --> 00:41:05.800
whether it's from a workshop or a course.

00:41:05.800 --> 00:41:10.679
So that exporting and then like keeping a copy of it locally

00:41:10.719 --> 00:41:13.000
is another thing that I've done.

00:41:14.439 --> 00:41:17.399
And then the other thing is if you're also teaching,

00:41:17.399 --> 00:41:21.320
like if there is a GitHub repository connected

00:41:23.959 --> 00:41:26.399
to the project or the space,

00:41:26.399 --> 00:41:30.000
then, not space, I guess, the project, to the project,

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:33.560
the text files and the data files can be there as well.

00:41:33.560 --> 00:41:38.560
That doesn't solve sort of the packages side of things,

00:41:39.040 --> 00:41:41.239
but at least it solves the other content.

00:41:43.320 --> 00:41:44.159
Awesome.

00:41:46.959 --> 00:41:49.199
Let's go over to the question from Jason.

00:41:49.199 --> 00:41:52.919
Jason asked, I have an account for an academic researcher.

00:41:52.919 --> 00:41:55.919
Do I have to create a new account for teaching

00:41:55.919 --> 00:41:58.560
or kind of what would you suggest?

00:41:58.560 --> 00:42:00.199
I think it's gonna depend on the level of teaching

00:42:00.199 --> 00:42:01.040
that you're doing.

00:42:01.040 --> 00:42:04.159
I know there's some limits on that academic researcher plan

00:42:04.159 --> 00:42:07.760
in terms of how many people can come into your space.

00:42:07.800 --> 00:42:09.959
I'd recommend looking, either reaching out to us

00:42:09.959 --> 00:42:10.959
so that we can have a conversation

00:42:10.959 --> 00:42:13.040
about what exactly it is you're trying to accomplish

00:42:13.040 --> 00:42:15.239
or checking out what those instructor plans look like

00:42:15.239 --> 00:42:17.399
and see if that could also meet your needs.

00:42:19.959 --> 00:42:22.879
I'm gonna jump over to a Slido question

00:42:22.879 --> 00:42:25.360
that we got a bit earlier.

00:42:25.360 --> 00:42:28.120
I think someone asked maybe a little bit more generally

00:42:28.120 --> 00:42:30.159
about just teaching data courses.

00:42:30.159 --> 00:42:32.399
They said, do you have a favorite piece of advice

00:42:32.399 --> 00:42:35.899
you've received related to teaching data courses?

00:42:38.560 --> 00:42:39.840
I'll try to take this.

00:42:39.840 --> 00:42:44.840
So I would say, I think the best advice that I've received

00:42:46.239 --> 00:42:50.239
has been around trying to get a sense

00:42:50.239 --> 00:42:52.479
of like the background of your students,

00:42:52.479 --> 00:42:55.280
which is, you know, in a way easy to do

00:42:55.280 --> 00:42:56.959
at the university level

00:42:56.959 --> 00:43:00.719
because there are prerequisites associated with the course

00:43:00.719 --> 00:43:05.199
and these are like strictly enforced generally.

00:43:05.239 --> 00:43:08.199
So you kind of have a sense of the background

00:43:08.199 --> 00:43:11.719
of your students or the lack of a background

00:43:11.719 --> 00:43:14.199
of your students in the content that you're teaching.

00:43:14.199 --> 00:43:17.919
But when I teach workshops, that's not necessarily the case.

00:43:17.919 --> 00:43:22.439
So something where if possible doing a short survey

00:43:22.439 --> 00:43:25.239
where you can get a sense of what they know

00:43:25.239 --> 00:43:26.959
and what they don't know ahead of time,

00:43:26.959 --> 00:43:28.800
I find to be really helpful.

00:43:28.800 --> 00:43:30.600
And I'll be honest, that's not to say

00:43:30.600 --> 00:43:33.719
that then I tailor the entire workshop

00:43:34.679 --> 00:43:36.399
based on the data that I get from them

00:43:36.399 --> 00:43:38.760
because that's usually not possible.

00:43:38.760 --> 00:43:40.560
People, you know, sign up for a workshop

00:43:40.560 --> 00:43:43.080
knowing what the content is or having read

00:43:43.080 --> 00:43:44.639
what the content is going to be.

00:43:44.639 --> 00:43:48.679
But I think it does change how I articulate certain things

00:43:48.679 --> 00:43:52.179
and how much time I spend on certain details.

00:43:52.179 --> 00:43:54.280
So that would be one thing.

00:43:54.280 --> 00:43:57.479
And then the other thing is, you know,

00:43:57.479 --> 00:44:02.399
I think live coding is one of the best things

00:44:02.399 --> 00:44:07.399
for teaching data courses of any kind,

00:44:08.360 --> 00:44:11.199
whether that's like a long-term course at the university

00:44:11.199 --> 00:44:12.800
or a short workshop.

00:44:12.800 --> 00:44:15.439
And with live coding, I find it really helpful

00:44:15.439 --> 00:44:18.580
to be able to do the live coding in the same environment

00:44:18.580 --> 00:44:20.040
that your students are doing it.

00:44:20.040 --> 00:44:23.439
Because I think one of the most frustrating things

00:44:23.439 --> 00:44:28.120
for learners tend to be, no, I ran the same code you ran,

00:44:28.120 --> 00:44:30.800
but I'm getting different results.

00:44:30.800 --> 00:44:33.000
It's never exactly different results,

00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:35.840
but maybe something looks slightly different

00:44:35.840 --> 00:44:37.040
or they're getting an error

00:44:37.040 --> 00:44:38.760
because they haven't installed a package

00:44:38.760 --> 00:44:41.199
that you have installed or something like that.

00:44:41.199 --> 00:44:43.719
So just being able to sort of do the live coding

00:44:43.719 --> 00:44:47.399
in the same environment is really important.

00:44:47.399 --> 00:44:51.000
So I think one of the sort of the best pieces of advice

00:44:51.000 --> 00:44:54.399
I've received was to do more and more live coding

00:44:54.399 --> 00:44:58.120
and anything that facilitates that I find very helpful.

00:44:59.120 --> 00:45:00.600
Yeah, the one thing that I heard

00:45:00.600 --> 00:45:02.239
was don't try to teach too much.

00:45:02.239 --> 00:45:03.959
Like I first started teaching, right?

00:45:03.959 --> 00:45:05.199
And like I was given a textbook

00:45:05.199 --> 00:45:06.600
and they said, this is what you're teaching.

00:45:06.600 --> 00:45:09.040
And I try to teach every single thing in that chapter

00:45:09.040 --> 00:45:10.959
where especially like at the intro level,

00:45:10.959 --> 00:45:15.159
I found like you wanna get people's appetite up for data.

00:45:15.159 --> 00:45:16.959
You want them to be excited enough to go on

00:45:16.959 --> 00:45:18.560
and learn bigger and better things

00:45:18.560 --> 00:45:20.239
and cramming everything down their throats

00:45:20.239 --> 00:45:22.879
in a limited period of time wasn't that helpful.

00:45:22.879 --> 00:45:24.840
I mean, I also mentioned like running a survey

00:45:24.840 --> 00:45:26.199
to understand them.

00:45:26.199 --> 00:45:27.919
The other thing that I would recommend

00:45:28.679 --> 00:45:29.520
that I thought worked well

00:45:29.520 --> 00:45:31.919
was making the data that they're initially looking into,

00:45:31.919 --> 00:45:32.760
especially with people

00:45:32.760 --> 00:45:34.280
that don't really understand data at all,

00:45:34.280 --> 00:45:35.959
data that they generated

00:45:35.959 --> 00:45:37.320
because then they really understand

00:45:37.320 --> 00:45:39.159
where it's coming from and what it is.

00:45:39.159 --> 00:45:41.080
And this can be as simple as saying,

00:45:41.080 --> 00:45:43.199
an anonymous survey and then throwing up,

00:45:43.199 --> 00:45:45.919
weight and height and turning that into like a correlation,

00:45:45.919 --> 00:45:47.239
regression type analysis,

00:45:47.239 --> 00:45:49.000
because people can see their data turning

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:50.840
into something meaningful right away.

00:45:50.840 --> 00:45:52.600
And I found that was always useful.

00:45:54.399 --> 00:45:55.239
That's awesome.

00:45:55.239 --> 00:45:56.199
Thanks for sharing.

00:45:57.199 --> 00:45:59.959
So I'll go on to the next question that we received

00:45:59.959 --> 00:46:01.679
and this one's from Nikki.

00:46:01.679 --> 00:46:04.159
She asked, what suggestions do you have

00:46:04.159 --> 00:46:06.840
for seamlessly utilizing PositCloud

00:46:06.840 --> 00:46:09.719
and Canvas LMS in a course?

00:46:12.159 --> 00:46:14.840
Yeah, right now we don't have any formal integrations.

00:46:14.840 --> 00:46:17.320
I do know some universities are experimenting

00:46:17.320 --> 00:46:19.199
with ways of people exporting things

00:46:19.199 --> 00:46:20.520
from work on PositCloud

00:46:20.520 --> 00:46:22.399
and then uploading those into Canvas

00:46:22.399 --> 00:46:24.600
for subsequent grading.

00:46:24.679 --> 00:46:26.159
I don't think we've got a great use case

00:46:26.159 --> 00:46:27.919
there built in right now.

00:46:27.919 --> 00:46:29.080
Minnie, have you attempted anything

00:46:29.080 --> 00:46:31.760
or are these separate environments?

00:46:31.760 --> 00:46:32.959
Separate environments.

00:46:32.959 --> 00:46:35.479
So we also use Canvas,

00:46:35.479 --> 00:46:40.479
but my students will export their sort of PDFs

00:46:41.080 --> 00:46:43.199
of the assignments that they're working on

00:46:43.199 --> 00:46:46.000
and then we'll upload them to Gradescope basically,

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:49.199
but it's they're doing the exporting and uploading.

00:46:49.199 --> 00:46:51.959
We don't have a sort of a connection between the two.

